Crypto CEX Market Data Connectivity — Specification v0.1
1. Objective
Build a high-performance Rust connectivity service for crypto centralized exchanges, starting with Binance Spot and Binance Futures.

The service must collect live market data, normalize it into internal binary messages, publish it to trading algorithms through Aeron, and provide enough redundancy, observability, and replay capability for high-frequency trading use cases.

2. Initial Scope
Phase 1 — Binance Market Data
Supported venues:

Binance Spot
Binance USD-M Futures
Supported protocols:

WebSocket JSON
Binance Spot SBE market data where available
REST API for snapshots, reference data, and recovery
Supported outbound transport:

Aeron IPC for local same-host consumers
Aeron UDP for cross-host consumers
Aeron Archive for recording/replay, if enabled
3. Required Data Feeds
3.1 Critical Live Feeds
Best Bid/Offer
Purpose:

Fast top-of-book view
Spread monitoring
Simple market making
Cross-exchange arbitrage
Health checks against full local book
Required fields:

venue
market type: spot, futures
symbol
exchange event timestamp
local receive timestamp
best bid price
best bid quantity
best ask price
best ask quantity
exchange update id, where available
Priority: Mandatory.

L2 Incremental Order Book
Purpose:

Maintain local order book
Compute order book imbalance
Detect pressure, queue changes, liquidity withdrawal
Feed execution algos and alpha models
Required fields:

venue
symbol
first update id
final update id
previous update id, where available
exchange event timestamp
exchange transaction timestamp, where available
local receive timestamp
bid updates: price, quantity
ask updates: price, quantity
Priority: Mandatory.

The system must validate sequence continuity. If a sequence gap is detected, the local book must be marked stale and rebuilt from a fresh REST snapshot plus buffered WebSocket updates.

Trades
Purpose:

Aggressor flow
Short-term momentum
Trade imbalance
Toxicity detection
VWAP and micro-price features
Required fields:

venue
symbol
trade id or aggregate trade id
price
quantity
trade timestamp
local receive timestamp
aggressor side if derivable
buyer-is-maker flag if provided
Priority: Mandatory.

For Spot, prefer raw trade stream when available. Aggregate trades can be collected as an additional lower-volume feed. For Futures, aggregate trade stream is required.

3.2 Derivatives-Specific Feeds
Mark Price / Index Price / Funding Rate
Purpose:

Futures fair value
Liquidation risk
Basis and funding models
Risk checks before sending orders
Required fields:

symbol
mark price
index price
funding rate
next funding time
exchange event timestamp
local receive timestamp
Priority: Mandatory for futures.

Liquidation Stream
Purpose:

Stress detection
Market regime detection
Short-term directional signals
Volatility and liquidity-risk monitoring
Required fields:

symbol
side
order type
time in force
original quantity
price
average price
order status
last filled quantity
exchange event timestamp
local receive timestamp
Priority: Recommended for futures.

Open Interest and Long/Short Data
Purpose:

Medium-frequency risk and regime signals
Funding/basis models
Positioning context
Collection mode:

REST polling
Not part of the lowest-latency path
Priority: Optional in Phase 1, recommended in Phase 2.

3.3 Reference and State Data
Instrument Metadata
Purpose:

Normalize all symbols into internal instrument ids
Validate price and quantity precision
Validate tick size, step size, min notional, contract type, status
Required fields:

venue
symbol
base asset
quote asset
market type
tick size
step size
min quantity
min notional
contract size, where applicable
trading status
onboard/delist timestamps, where applicable
Collection mode:

REST at startup
Periodic refresh
Refresh on detected symbol-status change
Priority: Mandatory.

Order Book Snapshots
Purpose:

Build initial local book
Recover after sequence gap
Periodic book validation
Required fields:

symbol
snapshot update id
bid levels
ask levels
local receive timestamp
Priority: Mandatory.

3.4 Private Account and Execution Feeds
These are required once the system sends orders.

Required events:

Order accepted
Order rejected
Order canceled
Order expired
Trade execution
Partial fill
Full fill
Balance update
Position update
Margin update
Funding fee update
Priority: Not required for market-data-only Phase 1, mandatory before live trading.

4. Normalized Internal Message Model
All outbound messages must be binary encoded and versioned.

Common header:

schema version
message type
venue id
market type
instrument id
source connection id
publisher instance id
sequence number
exchange event timestamp
exchange transaction timestamp, optional
local receive timestamp
local publish timestamp
Message types:

InstrumentDefinition
TradingStatus
BookSnapshot
BookDelta
BestBidOffer
Trade
MarkPrice
FundingRate
Liquidation
OpenInterest
AccountUpdate
OrderUpdate
Heartbeat
FeedStatus
GapDetected
BookStale
BookRecovered
Numeric representation:

Prices and quantities must not use floating point.
Use scaled integers or fixed-point decimals.
Each instrument definition must define price scale and quantity scale.
5. Connectivity Process Design
Each connector instance contains:

Connection manager Handles WebSocket lifecycle, reconnects, ping/pong, subscription state, and forced 24-hour reconnects.

REST client Fetches exchange info, depth snapshots, server time, open interest, and recovery data.

Decoder Parses JSON or SBE into exchange-native structs.

Normalizer Converts exchange-native messages into internal messages.

Order book engine Maintains local L2 book per symbol, validates update sequence, detects gaps, and handles rebuild.

Publisher Publishes normalized messages to Aeron.

Recorder Optionally writes raw inbound messages and normalized outbound messages to local storage or Aeron Archive.

Metrics and health module Publishes latency, message rate, reconnect count, stale books, dropped messages, and sequence gaps.

6. Aeron Publication Layout
Recommended initial layout:

One Aeron stream for normalized market data per venue/market/shard.
One Aeron stream for feed status.
One Aeron stream for reference data.
One Aeron stream for private execution/account data.
Optional raw-data stream for recording/debugging.
Example stream split:

binance.spot.md.shard.0
binance.spot.md.shard.1
binance.usdm.md.shard.0
binance.usdm.md.shard.1
binance.refdata
binance.status
binance.private
Each shard must have a single logical publisher to preserve deterministic sequence ordering.

7. Sharding Model
Symbols are assigned to connector shards using deterministic hashing:

instrument_id % total_shards == shard_id

Each instance receives:

instance_id
total_instances
venue
market type
symbol universe
shard assignment
The assignment must be deterministic so that active/standby and replay systems can reproduce the same routing.

8. Redundancy Model
Phase 1 redundancy:

Active/passive per shard.
Passive instance connects and validates data but does not publish as primary.
Passive can publish to a shadow Aeron stream for comparison.
Phase 2 redundancy:

Active/active duplicate collectors.
Downstream sequencer or arbiter selects the best feed per instrument.
Duplicate detection based on exchange update id and event timestamp.
Automatic failover when primary feed is stale.
Required feed states:

Connecting
Live
Degraded
Stale
Recovering
Recovered
Failed
9. Latency Requirements
Every message must carry at least:

exchange event timestamp
local receive timestamp
local publish timestamp
Metrics:

exchange event to local receive latency
local receive to publish latency
publish to algo receive latency
sequence gap count
reconnect count
stale book count
messages per second
bytes per second
parse time
normalization time
Aeron offer failure/backpressure count
Initial target:

Avoid allocations in hot path after startup.
Avoid floating point conversion in hot path.
Avoid string symbol lookup in hot path.
Publish binary messages with preallocated buffers.
Pin hot feed threads where possible.
Use bounded queues only where strictly necessary.
10. AWS Deployment
Recommended initial topology:

One Auto Scaling group or ECS service per venue/market type.
Instances deployed in a low-latency placement group when algorithms consume data in the same Availability Zone.
Separate redundancy group in another Availability Zone for disaster recovery.
Time synchronization configured on every host.
Metrics exported to Prometheus-compatible monitoring.
Logs written asynchronously and never on the hot path.
For lowest latency:

Benchmark AWS regions empirically against Binance endpoints.
Keep connector and algo processes in the same Availability Zone when using Aeron UDP.
Prefer Aeron IPC for same-host communication.
Use dedicated instances or isolated hosts for production trading.
Disable unnecessary OS services.
Tune CPU governor, NIC queues, socket buffers, and kernel networking parameters.
11. Rust Implementation Requirements
Runtime:

Rust stable
Linux x86_64
Tokio or equivalent only for network I/O
Hot-path processing should avoid unnecessary async boundaries
Performance requirements:

Preallocated buffers
Zero-copy parsing where possible
No heap allocation in steady-state book updates
Fixed-point numeric representation
Lock-free or single-writer data structures in hot path
Per-symbol order book owned by one thread/shard
Backpressure handling for Aeron publication failure
Graceful degradation when consumers are slow
Suggested internal crates/modules:

connector-core
binance-spot-adapter
binance-futures-adapter
protocol-json
protocol-sbe
order-book
refdata
aeron-publisher
metrics
replay
config
12. Recovery Rules
The connector must rebuild a local book when:

WebSocket reconnects
Sequence gap is detected
Snapshot update id is incompatible with buffered events
No book update is received within configured stale timeout
Parser detects malformed event
Exchange sends shutdown or maintenance event
Recovery procedure:

Mark book stale.
Continue buffering incoming deltas.
Fetch REST depth snapshot.
Discard buffered events older than snapshot update id.
Validate first applicable event bridges the snapshot.
Apply buffered events.
Mark book recovered.
Publish BookRecovered event.
13. Acceptance Criteria for Phase 1
The system is acceptable when:

It can collect Binance Spot BBO, trades, and L2 book deltas.
It can collect Binance USD-M Futures BBO, aggregate trades, L2 book deltas, mark price, funding, and liquidations.
It can build and maintain a valid local order book.
It detects and recovers from sequence gaps.
It publishes normalized binary messages through Aeron.
It records raw or normalized data for replay.
It exposes latency and health metrics.
It supports multiple connector instances with deterministic sharding.
It survives WebSocket disconnect/reconnect without manual intervention.
It runs continuously for more than 24 hours with planned connection rotation.
Market Data Connectivity — Spec Addendum v0.2
1. Recovery Buffering Policy
1.1 Principle
Book deltas must never be silently dropped.

If the connector cannot guarantee a continuous order book sequence, the book must be marked stale, publication of that book must stop, and recovery must restart from a fresh REST snapshot.

1.2 Buffer Types
Each symbol has a dedicated recovery buffer used only while the book is initializing or recovering.

The recovery buffer is not the normal runtime queue. In normal operation, book deltas are applied immediately by the shard thread.

1.3 Default Limits
Per symbol:

Limit	Default
Max buffered delta events	2,048
Max buffered bytes	4 MiB
Max buffer age	10 seconds
Max recovery attempts before circuit break	5
Circuit-break cooldown	30 seconds
Per connector process:

Limit	Default
Max total recovery buffer memory	512 MiB
Max symbols recovering at once	10% of assigned symbols, minimum 10
Max concurrent REST snapshot requests	Configurable, default 8
1.4 Overflow Behaviour
If a symbol recovery buffer exceeds event, byte, or age limits:

Drop the recovery buffer.
Mark the symbol book as STALE.
Publish BookStale.
Restart the recovery process from a new REST snapshot.
Increment recovery_buffer_overflow_total.
If repeated overflow occurs, put the symbol into DEGRADED state and reduce recovery retry frequency.
The connector must not publish deltas for a stale book.

1.5 Feed-Specific Overflow Policy
Feed	Drop allowed?	Overflow action
Book delta	No	Mark book stale and recover
BBO	No silent drop	Publish latest only if explicitly configured as conflated BBO
Trades	No in production	If configured for research mode, drop oldest and publish TradeGap
Mark price / funding	Yes, latest-value semantics	Keep latest value
Ticker / stats	Yes	Keep latest value
Liquidation	No preferred	Drop only under explicit degraded mode
Reference data	No	Retry until success or fail startup
2. Order Book Validation
2.1 Validation Layers
The connector must validate books using four layers:

Sequence validation
Top-of-book validation
Snapshot validation
Cross-instance validation
2.2 Sequence Validation
For Spot:

Ignore deltas where u <= local_last_update_id.
If U > local_last_update_id + 1, the book has missed events.
Mark stale and rebuild.
For USD-M Futures:

First applicable event must bridge the REST snapshot update id.
During live processing, each event’s pu must equal the previous event’s u.
If not, mark stale and rebuild.
2.3 Top-of-Book Validation
For every applied book delta:

Best bid must be strictly less than best ask.
Best bid and ask quantities must be positive.
Empty bid or ask side is invalid during normal trading.
Local top of book should match the exchange BBO stream when both are fresh.
If local book and BBO stream disagree:

Case	Action
One-off mismatch lasting less than 250 ms	Increment warning metric
Mismatch lasting more than 250 ms	Mark symbol DEGRADED
Mismatch lasting more than 1 second	Mark book STALE and rebuild
2.4 Snapshot Validation
Periodic REST snapshot validation is used as a slow correctness check, not as the primary source of truth.

Default policy:

Validate top 20 levels every 60 seconds for high-priority symbols.
Validate top 5 levels every 5 minutes for low-priority symbols.
Validate immediately after recovery.
Do not compare snapshots that are too old relative to local event time.
Snapshot validation tolerance:

Field	Tolerance
Price level existence	Exact for top N when comparable
Price value	Exact integer tick value
Quantity	Exact if snapshot timestamp/update id is comparable
Quantity	Warning only if snapshot is stale or update id is not comparable
2.5 Cross-Instance Validation
In active/passive mode, passive collectors should maintain their own books and publish checksums to a status stream.

Each instance publishes:

Symbol
Local update id
Best bid/ask
Top 5 checksum
Top 20 checksum
Last exchange event timestamp
Last local receive timestamp
Recovery state
The monitor compares active and passive instances.

If checksums diverge:

Check sequence freshness.
Prefer the instance with the newer valid sequence.
If both claim valid but disagree for more than 500 ms, mark the symbol suspect.
If divergence persists for more than 2 seconds, trigger active/passive failover or rebuild both books.
3. SBE Protocol
3.1 Source of Truth
SBE decoding must be generated from the official Binance Spot SBE XML schema.

Reverse-engineered schemas are not allowed.

The schema file must be versioned in the repository and include:

Original upstream schema file
Generated Rust decoder code
Schema id
Schema version
Semantic version
Generation timestamp
Code generator version
3.2 Supported SBE Messages
Initial supported SBE stream messages:

TradesStreamEvent
BestBidAskStreamEvent
DepthSnapshotStreamEvent
DepthDiffStreamEvent
3.3 SBE Implementation Requirement
The protocol-sbe crate must provide:

Decoder for official Binance Spot SBE stream schema
Schema-version validation at startup
Compatibility checks for minor schema version changes
Fallback to JSON if SBE is unavailable
Golden binary fixtures from captured Binance messages
Unit tests comparing SBE-decoded output with equivalent JSON-normalized messages
3.4 SBE Runtime Policy
Preferred feed order for Binance Spot:

SBE stream for trade, BBO, and depth where supported.
JSON WebSocket fallback.
REST only for snapshots and reference data.
4. Shard Count and Instance Count
4.1 Principle
Shard count is fixed for a deployment generation.

Instance count can change, but shard ids must remain stable.

Do not assign symbols directly to instances. Assign symbols to logical shards, then assign shards to instances.

4.2 Recommended Model
Use:

symbol -> instrument_id -> logical_shard_id -> instance_id
Where:

logical_shard_id = hash(venue, market_type, symbol) % total_logical_shards
instance_id = logical_shard_id % active_instance_count
4.3 Initial Defaults
Deployment size	Logical shards	Expected use
Small	16	Initial prototype
Medium	64	Full Binance Spot or Futures
Large	128+	Multi-exchange, many symbols
Do not use “1 shard = 1 instance”.

A good starting point is:

4 to 16 logical shards per physical instance.
One hot processing thread per active shard group.
Keep high-volume symbols isolated when needed.
4.4 Dynamic Scaling
Changing total_logical_shards requires a deployment generation change.

A deployment generation change must:

Start new connector group.
Build books in shadow mode.
Compare active and shadow feeds.
Switch downstream algos to new generation.
Stop old generation.
No in-place shard-count mutation is allowed in Phase 1.

5. Aeron Configuration and Backpressure
5.1 Initial Aeron Channel Defaults
For same-host connector-to-algo communication:

aeron:ipc
For cross-host communication inside the same AWS placement group:

aeron:udp?endpoint=<host>:<port>|mtu=1408|term-length=64m
Initial defaults:

Parameter	Default
MTU	1408 bytes
Term length	64 MiB
Media driver threading	Dedicated
Aeron directory	/dev/shm/aeron
Idle strategy	Busy spin for production hot path
Archive recording	Enabled for market-data streams
These are benchmark defaults, not final constants. They must be validated under real message rates.

5.2 Publication Model
Each Aeron publication is owned by one shard thread.

No multiple-writer publication in the hot path.

Each message has:

Connector sequence number
Aeron stream id
Aeron session id
Publication timestamp
Source instance id
Source shard id
5.3 Backpressure Policy
The connector must not block the WebSocket read loop indefinitely.

On Aeron offer failure:

Retry with bounded spin for a very short configured budget.
If still backpressured, publish a local metric.
If backpressure persists, mark publication DEGRADED.
If backpressure exceeds the configured maximum, disconnect/restart the affected shard or fail over to another instance.
Default policy:

Condition	Action
Offer fails briefly	Spin/retry
Offer fails > 100 µs	Increment warning metric
Offer fails > 1 ms	Mark stream degraded
Offer fails > 10 ms	Trigger shard restart or failover
Offer fails repeatedly	Stop publishing and mark feed failed
For order book deltas, do not drop and continue as if healthy.

For latest-value feeds, optional conflation is allowed only if configured.

6. Private Execution Data
6.1 Phase
Private execution data should be Phase 1.5, not Phase 2.

Reason: before live trading, the system needs order-state correctness, fill correlation, latency measurement, and reconciliation.

6.2 Required Components
Phase 1.5 must include:

Order gateway
Client order id generator
Order state machine
User data stream listener
Execution report normalizer
REST reconciliation process
Drop-copy or secondary account listener where available
Persistent order journal
6.3 Correlation Keys
Every outbound order must include an internal client order id.

Correlation keys:

Internal order id
Venue order id
Client order id
Strategy id
Account id
Symbol
Side
Price
Quantity
Order creation timestamp
Local send timestamp
The order state machine must handle:

Acknowledgement before REST response
Execution before acknowledgement
Cancel acknowledgement after fill
Unknown order status after timeout
Duplicate execution report
Out-of-order execution events
STP expiry
Amend/replace events
6.4 Reconciliation
The system must reconcile:

Open orders
Recent fills
Balances
Positions
Funding fees
Commissions
Reconciliation must run:

At startup
After reconnect
After unknown order status
Periodically in the background
Before enabling live trading after failover
7. Latency SLA
7.1 Timestamping
Every message must carry:

Exchange event timestamp
Exchange transaction timestamp, if provided
Local socket receive timestamp
Decode completion timestamp
Book apply timestamp
Aeron publication timestamp
Algo receive timestamp, added by consumer
7.2 Initial Internal Latency Targets
These targets exclude exchange publication delay and public internet/network path.

Hop	Target p50	Target p99
Socket receive → decoded native message	< 10 µs	< 50 µs
Decode → normalized internal message	< 5 µs	< 25 µs
Book delta apply	< 10 µs	< 50 µs
Normalize → Aeron offer	< 5 µs	< 25 µs
Aeron IPC publish → local algo receive	< 10 µs	< 50 µs
Connector hot-path total, receive → publish	< 50 µs	< 250 µs
Stretch target:

local socket receive → Aeron publish p99 < 100 µs
Do not define SLA as “exchange event timestamp to local receive” because that includes exchange-side batching, internet route, AWS region, and clock differences. Track it, but do not treat it as a deterministic software SLA.

7.3 Stale Book SLA
Event	Target
Gap detection	Immediate on offending event
Mark stale	< 100 µs after gap detection
Snapshot request start	< 10 ms
Normal recovery	< 2 seconds
Recovery alert	> 5 seconds
Circuit break	> 5 failed recoveries or > 30 seconds stale
8. Testing and Replay
8.1 Required Test Types
The project must include:

Unit tests for parsers
Unit tests for order book apply logic
Golden-file tests for JSON and SBE messages
Property tests for order book invariants
Integration tests with recorded Binance data
Stress tests with synthetic high-volume symbols
Chaos tests for disconnects and REST slowness
Replay tests through Aeron
8.2 Market Data Replayer
The system must include a replayer that can replay:

Raw WebSocket payloads
Normalized internal messages
Aeron Archive recordings
Replay modes:

Mode	Description
As-fast-as-possible	Max throughput test
Original timing	Preserve original inter-message gaps
Scaled timing	Replay at 2x, 10x, 100x speed
Deterministic	Same input produces same output sequence
Fault injection	Inject gaps, duplicates, reorderings, and delays
8.3 Symbol Universe Testing
The test harness must support:

1 symbol
10 symbols
100 symbols
1,000+ symbols
Top-volume symbols only
Full exchange symbol universe
Mixed spot and futures symbols
Synthetic tests must include:

High update-rate BTC/ETH-like symbols
Illiquid symbols
Symbols with zero updates
Delisting/trading halt events
Wide spreads
Empty side edge cases
Large price-level update batches
9. Exchange-Specific Quirks Matrix
The codebase must include a venue quirks matrix.

9.1 Binance Spot
Known quirks:

24-hour WebSocket connection lifetime.
Server sends ping frames; client must respond with pong.
Incoming client messages are rate-limited.
Maximum streams per connection.
JSON timestamps are milliseconds by default unless microsecond mode is requested.
SBE timestamps are microseconds.
Local book recovery uses U, u, and REST lastUpdateId.
Depth snapshots are capped and do not guarantee knowledge of levels outside the snapshot.
User data listen-key streams are deprecated in favor of WebSocket API user data streams.
9.2 Binance USD-M Futures
Known quirks:

Market streams use routed URL paths such as /public, /market, and /private.
Depth events include U, u, and pu.
Correct live sequence requires pu == previous.u.
Depth updates may be 100 ms, 250 ms, or 500 ms depending on stream.
RPI orders are excluded from normal diff depth.
User order updates arrive as ORDER_TRADE_UPDATE.
Fast trade-lite private execution events may be available but contain fewer fields.
9.3 Required Quirk Documentation Fields
Each venue adapter must document:

WebSocket URL
Authentication model
Compression behaviour
Ping/pong policy
Connection lifetime
Subscription rate limits
Max streams per connection
Sequence fields
Snapshot endpoint
Snapshot depth limit
Recovery algorithm
Timestamp units
Numeric encoding
Known breaking changes
Test fixtures
10. Active/Active Failover and Arbiter
10.1 Modes
Supported modes:

Active/passive
Active/active with shadow validation
Active/active with arbiter-selected publication
Phase 1 should implement active/passive.

Phase 2 should implement active/active arbitration.

10.2 Arbiter Input
Each collector publishes feed-quality metadata:

Instance id
Shard id
Symbol
Feed state
Last update id
Last event timestamp
Last local receive timestamp
Gap count
Recovery count
BBO/book mismatch count
Top 5 checksum
Publish latency
Exchange-to-local latency estimate
Aeron backpressure count
10.3 Arbiter Selection Rules
The arbiter chooses the best feed per symbol using this priority order:

Feed must be LIVE.
Sequence must be valid.
Book must not be stale.
Prefer newer update id.
Prefer lower local receive latency.
Prefer lower gap/recovery count.
Prefer matching passive checksums.
Prefer configured primary instance if all else is equal.
10.4 Failover Thresholds
Condition	Action
No update for stale timeout	Switch to backup
Sequence gap	Switch to backup if backup is valid
Book/BBO mismatch > 1s	Switch or rebuild
Aeron backpressure > threshold	Switch
Process heartbeat missed	Switch
AWS instance unhealthy	Switch
Failover must publish:

Old source instance
New source instance
Symbol or shard affected
Reason
Last valid update id
Failover timestamp
10.5 Duplicate Handling
In active/active mode, duplicate events are identified by:

Venue
Symbol
Message type
Exchange update id or trade id
Event timestamp
Price/quantity payload hash when needed
The arbiter must guarantee downstream algorithms receive one canonical sequence per symbol.


